                                   Part 1:*2@5


  My first car was a@1 1986 Ford Escort Mk3@5 with a red pearlesant paint job,   4
  new  wheel  arches,   a  new 1.3 engine with  44,000  miles  on  it  and  an
  earbusting  face off stereo system.  I bought it in April  '98  having  just
  past my Theory,  Practical and advanced driving test first time. I bought it
  for  £500 and the insurance was £600.  I didn't care,  I just wanted to  get
  out  in  that  car  and drive it on my own without someone taking  over  the
  controls or shouting down my ear.  I was 18 so as you can imagine it was  my
  pride  and joy.  I  was washing it all the time,  vacuuming it and  cleaning
  every speck of dust off of it.  But still something was missing. Being an 18
  year old@1 "Boy Racer / Raver"@5 this car needed to look like the business  even
  if  it  couldn't  race  a  plastic pig and win.  But  money  is  always  the
  deciding  factor  at this age and having just bought this car,  insured  and
  taxed it I couldn't even afford to fill the tank up.  Luck did pass  my  way
  though as I had a friend who lived very close to me with a Mk2 Escort  which
  had  more  rust than a rust factory.  On this particular Mk2 were very  nice
  FAT  steel 13" wheels with recessed centre sections.  They definitely looked
  better  than my boring old Mk3 wheels so since my mate was selling  the  car
  for  scrap I decided to swap wheels  with him.  I did particularly well  out
  of  this since my old tyres had absolutely no tread on them and the new ones
  where practically brand new.  My friend with the Mk2 finally sold it for £80
  to someone who wanted the engine for a kit-car.

  Fitting the wheels was the fun part.  I wouldn't be surprised if the  wheels
  I  had on it before where the original ones put on at the bloody factory.  I
  was jumping up and down on the wheel brace as though my life depended on  it
  while my girlfriend was blowing the new tyres up with a foot pump.  It was a
  stupendous  sight.  In the end we had to drive it to  the  local  garage  to
  loosen the nuts with an air gun.
  The  next  day  I went out to my car to visit my friend and the  damn  thing
  wouldn't  start.  Being new in this game I was puzzled at what  it  was.   I
  opened  the bonnet to see that the distributor cap was hanging  off  but  it
  wouldn't screw back in because the "bit" it goes into had knackered threads.
  Out  with the cable ties!  It's still connected with two cable ties to  this
  very  day.   While I was under the bonnet I checked a few other things.   It
  turns  out  that the air filter was as black as liqourice and one  pipe  (to
  the manifold I think)  was completely missing.  Off to the scrap yard on the
  Redditch by pass we go.
  On  arrival at the scrap yard we started demolishing the first XR3i we could
  find.  We had practically stripped the car bare when someone came out of the
  little  hut which said@1 "WE ARE WATCHING!"@5 on the side of it next to  a  sign
  which said@1 "OUR DOG EATS THIEVES"@5. The person shouted@4 "what the f**k are you
  doing to that car!!!!"@5.  After my friend had managed to rip the spoiler  off
  an another and  managed to destroyed a pair of  glasses  he'd  found  in the
  glovebox  I  said  sheepishly@3 "how much do you want for the alloys,   seats,
  spoiler, and steering wheel?"@5.
  @4

  "That car isn't for sale,  it's been in a minor accident and is being stored
  here. Does it look like a breaker to you?"
  @3
            "This IS a breakers yard isn't it?"@5 I said sarcastically.
  @4
             "What you after?"@5 he said as he was losing his patience.
  @3
  "Erm .  .  .  . a new dash for my Escort."@5 I said@1 (I couldn't say a pipe and
                                                      an air filter could I?)
  @4
  "All the Escorts are over there"@5 he said pointing at a large pile of mangled
  Escorts.   Then he muttered something about the price of dashes  etc. as  he
  walked back to his hut.

  What  a  crap idea it was looking for a brand new air filter in  a  breakers
  yard.  We did however fill our pockets with the needed pipe,  about  5  gear
  knobs,  20 bulbs and approximately 40 fuses.  It's a good job we brought big
  coats.  It was heads down as we walked through the exit next to the  dreaded
  HUT,   then  a final dash to my car as we got a safe distance from  the  dog
  cage.  I  decided to fit all my newly stolen extras when I got back home. My
  friends agreed.


  So my car now had some new bulbs,  proper amp fuses, a Capri gearknob@1 (which
  it's  still got)@5  and a chunky Sierra steering wheel to replace that  crappy
  Escort one.  The next event was to wake up to a car with a nice dented  rear
  bumper  which was bent enough to scratch a bit of the paint.  I was  f**king
  @1FURIOUS!!!!!@5  This c**t must die.  I pulled the metal bumper back into shape
  and  felt  happy at the fact that it had probably done more  damage  to  the
  other persons car than mine.

  I  finally  got  up motor world and bought an air filter  so  my  car  could
  breathe  without conking out in first gear and to round it off  I  bought  a
  stainless  steel exhaust trim which I got on with a lot of WD-40,   a  screw
  and a huge kick.

  The  kick hadn't done all to good to the exhaust system as I found out about
  3 weeks later.  My car was sounding like a bleedin' Hot Rod,  jees that trim
  really  sounds good I thought.  The truth was that the backbox  was  falling
  off  and  a  lot of exhaust fumes where exiting in the wrong place.  Another
  trip  to the garage saw me back £80 for a backbox and mid section which  was
  also  riddled with holes.  I felt like replacing the downpipe  and  manifold
  as well, NO, might aswell replace the whole engine while I'm at it.@1 OH GET A
  GRIP.@5  That's the last time I buy an exhaust trim 2 times too small for  the
  exhaust.


  Since this was my pride and joy and even a dent in the bumper made me mad  I
  descided to invest in a security system.  It cost me a lot of money  but  it
  was Thatcham II approved so I got double that back off the insurance.  Now I
  had a cheaper premium and peace of mind. Great stuff.

  Being young,  happy and stupid I descided to push my luck with the road  and
  the  road  won.   Flying  round an island at about  30  MPH  at  10PM  in  a
  residential  area took its toll.  I turned a bit too soon as  there  was  an
  oncoming  car on the road I was coming onto.  The front left wheel  hit  the
  strangely  high  curb  and  launched my  car  into  the  air.   As  the  car
  straightened  up  the front left of my car started to  dip  and  I  heard  a
  flapping noise.  It was almost impossible to keep the car in a straight line
  so  I  dived into the curb and skidded to a stop.  I'm surprised  the  shock
  absorber  didn't come through the bonnet.  As I exited the car cursing I saw
  black  clouds looming over an already dark street and didn't like  the  look
  of things at all.  The tyre was split completely and was almost off the rim,
  the  steel wheel had a nice curb shaped dent in it and I was pissed off.   I
  got  the  kit out of the boot and had a choice as there were two  spares  in
  the  boot,  I chose the one with air in it.  I got the f**ked wheel off easy
  enough  but  whoever designed the shape of the inside wheel and  wheel  bolt
  for  the  Escort was a nutter because they are a bloody pain  in  the  arse,
  especially when it's raining. @1 OH NO DON'T RAIN!  BOLLOCKS!@5   I ran  to  the
  nearest house to phone my mom to pick me up planning on fixing it  the  next
  day.   I chose the first house with a light on in it.  An 80 year old  women
  came  to  the  door  and  spoke to me through the letter  box.   I  gave  up
  immediately and went to the next house.  A semi naked women in her 20s  came
  to  the door and I described the situation.  She let me use her phone as she
  hid  on the other side of the door but the answer machine was on.  Oh  well,
  back to work.  After another attempt I was just losing my temper with it and
  threw the wheel  brace on the ground. @1 (It's so much easier in the daylight.
  @5I  ran  back to my girlfriends house who I'd just dropped home.  She  opened
  the  door to see me dripping with rain and oil and got me a towel.  Her  dad
  found a torch,  lent me a coat and we braved the waters once more.  It  took
  about 2 minutes with a torch,  it seemed so easy but there you go. I had one
  odd  wheel but at least I could get home in one piece.  The next day I  went
  up  to Tyresales and they put a new tyre on it and bashed the huge dent  out
  of it. I was happy once more. I didn't drive like that ever again, but I did
  drive faster. #8 Read on.@5 The first problem I noticed with driving the car was
  when  sometimes  the indicators would flash at twice the speed  they  should
  do,   I  could tell this by the display and listening to what the relay  was
  doing,  I suppose it was about time to check the electrics out.   I  got  my
  mate to sit in the car and try the brakes, reverse gear, lights etc. while I
  looked  at  the  car from the rear.@1  WHAT THE F**KS GOING ON?@5 Sometimes  the
  brake  lights wouldn't work,  sometimes they would,  sometimes  the  reverse
  lights worked,  sometimes they decided that they were indicators after  all!
  I  couldn't understand why this was happening.  I looked inside the boot and
  removed the light clusters from their holders for a closer inspection,   the
  bulbs  were  okay but it looked like the wiring loom connectors  were  badly
  designed  and had quite a bit of rust on them,  maybe one day I would  clean
  them up.@2

  LOUD SIREN, @6 BLUE LIGHTS,@3 PANIC,@5 Oops, looks like I've been pulled over! Why
  did  they  have to pull me over now that I had got onto the main trunk  road
  in the rush hour with nowhere to stop?
  @3
                             "Hello, can I help you?"
  @7
