  warning, you must produce your documents at the police station though"
  @5
  After  taking  my  details  down  they   said  goodbye  and  apologised  for
  embarrassing me in front of my boss.  I got the  work  done  at  nearby  Ian
  Farrels motor company.  It cost £70 and it seemed they had done the job,   a
  bit pricy though.  I produced at the cop shop and all was well...... until a
  month  later.  What was wrong this time? Same problem!  I checked  the  rear
  lights  and  it looked like Ian Farrells had just replaced a few  pieces  of
  plastic in there.  That's one garage I wouldn't be using again.  In the  end
  after  a  miserable attempt at fixing them myself I  took  the  car  to  the
  local  specialist electrical place,  Goodwins.  They practically re-designed
  the  rear  light  clusters  for me and made damn  sure  there  would  be  no
  problems  with  them  in the future.  The guy told me  that  they  had  done
  hundreds  of Escorts and Sierras with the same problem and  that  it  was  a
  design  fault that was rectified somewhat with the mk4 and 5.  Not  bad  for
  £23 eh?


  My  sister  had a 1985 1.8 Nissan Bluebird with 108,000 miles on  the  clock
  and  it had been sitting on her drive for six months ever since she had  got
  their  new  people carrier with her boyfriend.  It was my job to  sell  this
  pile of shit.


  The  air filter was in worse state than my old one,  it was burning as  much
  oil  as  it  was fuel and the battery took 4 days to charge.  This monstrous
  car  still  wouldn't  start  no matter what.  You  could  hear  the  pistons
  scraping!!   My  brother in law who sold me the  Escort  came  round  to  my
  sisters and gave it the works.  He cleaned the points,  checked the  sparks,
  checked  the BLACK oil and gave it some jump leads from his Maestro  Diesel.
  It  took about half an hour but we finally got it started after finding  out
  this  car  had  an immobiliser which was probably worth more than  the  car.@5
  There  was  an almighty roar and a huge cloud of smoke but we had  done  it,
  She  was  alive!  When the smoke finally cleared we saw that the car  parked
  behind  it  had a new type of oily paint job.  At that point we descided  to
  pack  up  and leave.  Stage one complete I was looking forward to stage  two
  which  was  towing  this box back to my house without  getting  pulled.   It
  worked,  it took a bit longer than anticipated but it worked. I was flat out
  in second gear all the way. It felt like I was towing a bloody tank.
  @5

  You know when the sun shines on my car,  the paint really brightens up.   On
  this  Nissan all it did was highlight the rust and birdshit.  It took  me  a
  couple  of  days  to clean it inside and out,  but when I  had  finished  it
  didn't  look  all that bad.  I had to take it round the block  a  couple  of
  times  to  clear the system@1 (and to see what a 1.8 felt like)@5.   A  word  of
  advise,   if your going to buy a car as big as that make sure it  has  power
  steering.  I advertised the thing for £300 which was way more  than  it  was
  worth.   After a few weeks of lookers but no buyers my sister recommended  I
  put it in for an MOT.  It was risky driving it there but it was worth it  if
  it  somehow  passed.   The  nearest MOT station was  Baldwins  Lane  Service
  Station.   I used to live next to the owner of the place so I  was  sure  he
  wouldn't  rip me off.  It cost me £30 just to find out that it  needed  £250
  worth of fixing.  Suspension,  tyres, exhaust nothing real major but even so
  I  couldn't afford it so my sister said I could keep whatever I sold it  for
  since  I probably wouldn't get more that the price of the MOT for it.  After
  2  months  I was tired of seeing the thing out the front of my  house  so  I
  made  a  more concerned effort to sell it.  In the local paper was an advert
  for  an rare RS Motorsport contoured leather steering wheel which was  being
  sold for £75.  Why not I thought and gave them a ring. The steering wheel in
  question  was  a rare one which wasn't available to buy any more and  had  a
  boss kit suitable for my car fitted on it.

